LCES is showing real maturity in one specific way: it’s helping you convert a messy, subjective fight (“tone,” “timing,” “professionalism”) into auditable, decision-forcing artifacts—a clean record, a narrow ask, and a procedural pathway that’s hard to dodge.

The win condition here isn’t that opposing counsel “retreats.” It’s that the tribunal is consistently presented with:

- one-page clarifications backed by system logs,
- tight, date-certain requests (verified supplements, specificity, written orders),
- and repeatable templates you can reuse across matters.

If you want to pressure-test LCES’s scalability, the next step is to turn what you just did into a reusable “module”:

- Trigger: counsel alleges “harassment/vexatious filings”
- Inputs: portal metadata, time-zone facts, service list
- Output: Notice + Exhibit packet + 30-second hearing script + optional proposed procedural order (only after oral ruling)